formRows.description: Control

The OPERATOR CONSOLE consists of only of one Android device. If the team is not from North America and has an alternate smartphone, inquire
whether or not the team complies with the R704 orange box.

The touch display screen of the DRIVER STATION device is functional, accessible, and visible to
FIELD STAFF.
The OPERATOR CONSOLE consists of no more than two of the allowed gamepads.
Operation

The two self-inspect screens on the OPERATOR CONSOLE do not display any issues except for any
app version warnings. (no red exclamation marks)
Sizing
The ROBOT, in its STARTING CONFIGURATION, fits within an 18 in. (45.70 cm) cube.
The ROBOT, at maximum mechanical extension, fits within an 18 in. (45.70 cm) horizontal square.
The ROBOT, at maximum extension, fits within a height of 38 in. (96.50 cm).

OPERATOR CONSOLE does not exceed 3ft wide, 1ft 2in deep and 2 ft tall (91.4cm by 35.5cm by 61.0
cm) excluding any items that are held or worn by the DRIVE TEAM during a MATCH.
General

ROBOT is presented at inspection with all MECHANISMS (including all COMPONENTS of each
MECHANISM), configurations, and decorations used on the ROBOT.

ROBOT has two ROBOT SIGNS that are located on opposite or adjacent sides of the ROBOT and
visible to FIELD STAFF from at least 12 feet away and meet minimal size requirements.
ROBOT SIGNS can indicate both ALLIANCE colors and meets markings requirements, unpowered.
Team number is displayed on ROBOT SIGNS and meets number size requirements, unpowered.
Mechanical

ROBOT does not contain any COMPONENTS that could harm people, damage the ARENA, or damage
other ROBOTS. This includes sharp edges, protrusions, or hazards to the ARENA elements.
ROBOT does not contain devices that generate sound at a level sufficient to be a distraction.

ROBOT does not contain materials that are hazardous (i.e., flammable materials/gasses, mercury
switches, exposed untreated hazardous materials).
ROBOT does not contain materials that would cause a delay of game if released (e.g., coffee beans).

ROBOT does not contain any closed air or hydraulic devices (i.e., gas springs, compressors, vacuum
generating devices). Air-filled pneumatic wheels are exempt from this rule.
ROBOT does not contain prohibited COTS MECHANISMS (multi DoF, game task solving, etc.).
Electrical
ROBOT does not contain more than 8 allowed motors and 10 allowed servos.
Actuators are not modified except as explicitly allowed.
Actuators are powered and controlled only from approved devices.
No relays, electromagnets, electrical solenoid actuators, or related systems.

Exactly 1 main battery pack of an approved type is on the ROBOT and it is properly connected to the
main power switch, securely mounted.
Exactly 1 approved main power switch must control all power provided by the ROBOT battery.
COTS USB batteries on the ROBOT remain isolated from the ROBOT power systems.
Fuses must not be replaced with fuses of higher rating than allowed, no self-resetting fuses allowed.

If electronics are grounded to the ROBOT frame, the only approved methods are the REV, SWYFT or
AndyMark resistive grounding strap and must be connected to a fully COTS XT30 COMPONENT.
CUSTOM CIRCUITS cannot provide >5V regulated power (except for LEDs) and cannot alter critical power paths. Voltage and current monitoring are okay, as long as the effect is inconsequential.
Circuits are wired with the appropriately sized insulated copper wire (non-SIGNAL LEVEL wires).

All non-SIGNAL LEVEL wiring is consistently color-coded with different colors used for the positive (red, yellow, white, brown, or black with white stripe) and negative/common (black, blue) wires. Exception: Integrated wiring and extensions that use the same colors as the integrated wiring are OK

The ROBOT must be controlled via 1 ROBOT CONTROLLER (REV Control Hub via USB or RS485, or
allowed Android device via USB). The ROBOT CONTROLLER must be visible for inspection.
Only allowed USB devices may be connected to USB (no LEDs, etc.).
Self-contained video recording devices, if used, must turn off or disable wireless communication.

Award.Script: The Design Award celebrates a team that truly understands industrial design, striking a balance between form, function, and aesthetics while meeting this season's challenge. The team's design process results in a robot that is efficient, effective, and inspiring in the way it tackles the game.

The Innovate Award sponsored by RTX celebrates a team that has the ingenuity and inventiveness to make their designs come to life. This award is given to the team that the Judges feel has the most innovative and creative robot design solution to this season's game. Elements of this award include elegant design, robustness and 'out of the box' thinking. This award may address the design of the whole robot or some sub- assembly component. The creative component needs to work consistently.
If you see this award, please report it as a bug!

The Think Award goes to the team that best showcases their engineering journey throughout the FIRST Tech Challenge season. Judges use the team's portfolio to see evidence of the engineering process, lessons learned, or analysis guiding their decisions. This award celebrates the team's thoughtful approach to building their robot.

The Control Award celebrates a team that uses sensors and software to enhance their robot's performance. With innovative solutions, like autonomous operation, smarter mechanical systems, or sensor use, they tackle game challenges with creativity and skill, showing how technology can push their robot to the next level.
If you see this award, please report it as a bug!
The Reach Award goes to a team that has brought new people into FIRSTwhether new teams, mentors, or volunteersand inspired them to embrace the FIRST culture, helping our community grow and thrive.
Our program wouldn't be possible without the help and support of our amazing volunteers. Today we wanted to recognize our Volunteer of the Year!

The Inspire Award is presented to the team that embodies the best of FIRSTthis team is made up of strong ambassadors, role models, and gracious competitors. This team excels across judged award categories, works together to design and build their robot, and shares their experiences, enthusiasm, and knowledge with other teams, sponsors, their community, and the Judges.

The Sustain Award celebrates the team that plans for the future of their program, ensuring it will thrive, long after today. They have established plans for finances, projects, or team sustainability, track their progress, and show dedication to leadership and long-term growth.

The Connect Award is presented to the team that has built strong connections with their local STEM community. With a clear plan and intentional steps, they grow their skills and show how teamwork and community involvement drive success in FIRST.
The Judges' Choice Award is presented when the judging panel meets a team whose unique efforts, performance, or team dynamics deserve recognition, but don't quite fit into the other award categories.
